doc.ContractDescription: THE MIT INNOVATION LAB IS AN MIT-INDUSTRY COLLABORATION DEVOTED TO IMPROVING THE ABILITY OF FIRMS AND INSTITUTIONS TO GENERATE "BREAKTHROUGH" INNOVATIONS AND TECHNOLOGIES. THE LAB IS CHAIRED BY PROFESSOR ERIC VON HIPPEL. THE MIT INNOVATION LAB HOLDS 3 TWO-DAY MEETINGS PER YEAR. LAB MEETINGS SHIFT BETWEEN MIT AND MEMBER SITES. AT MEETINGS HELD AT MIT, THE PRIMARY FOCUS OF PRESENTATIONS AND DISCUSSION IS ON RECENT ACADEMIC DEVELOPMENTS IN CONCEPT DEVELOPMENT METHODOLOGIES. AT MEETINGS HELD AT MEMBER SITES, THE PRIMARY FOCUS IS ON METHODS EMPLOYED BY THOSE MEMBERS, AND DISCUSSIONS OF RECENT EXPERIMENTS THAT HAVE CARRIED OUT USING NEW CONCEPT DEVELOPMENT METHODOLOGIES. THE VALUE TO NASA OF PARTICIPATION IN THIS LAB IS EXCHANGE OF DETAILED INFORMATION ON INNOVATION PROCESSES WITH OTHER LEADING EXPERTS IN LARGE ORGANIZATIONS THAT ARE FACING COMMON NEEDS TO BE MORE AGILE, AND TO MORE EFFICIENTLY DRAW UPON OUTSIDE RESOURCES FOR IDEAS REGARDING NOVEL ORGANIZATIONAL APPROACHES TO INNOVATION THAT HAVE BEEN TESTED IN AT LEAST A SINGLE ORGANIZATION - AND THAT ARE EVALUATED AND DISCUSSED IN DETAIL BY MIT INNOVATION LAB MEMBERS AND HARVARD AND MIT ACADEMICS WITH EXPERTISE WHO HAVE DONE SCHOLARLY WORK ON THE TOPIC. LAB MEMBER COMPANIES WORK ON THEIR OWN INNOVATION AGENDA AS THEY CHOOSE. WE THEN EXCHANGE INFORMATION AND LEARNINGS WITH EACH OTHER AT OUR MEETINGS. THERE IS NO OBLIGATION FOR LAB MEMBERS TO SHARE THE TECHNIQUES THEY HAVE DEVELOPED OR USED WITH OTHER MEMBERS, BUT SO FAR ALL HAVE CHOSEN TO DO SO. LAB MEMBERSHIP IS RESTRICTED TO 6 CORPORATE AND INSTITUTIONAL MEMBERS PLUS RELEVANT MIT AND HARVARD UNIVERSITY RESEARCHERS SO THAT WE CAN KNOW EACH OTHER WELL, AND HAVE EFFICIENT SMALL-GROUP WORKSHOPS. CURRENT MEMBERS ARE GOOGLE, FORD, GENERAL MILLS, PITNEY-BOWES, AND GOODYEAR. AS A LAB MEMBER, NASA WILL BE GRANTED A SEAT AT THESE SMALL-GROUP MEETINGS.

doc.ContractDescription: IN THIS WORK, WE WILL USE MARS EXPLORATION ROVER (MER) NAVIGATION CAMERA (NAVCAM) IMAGES OF THE MARTIAN SKY POINTED NEAR THE SUN THAT CONTAIN THE FORWARD-SCATTERING LOBE OF THE AEROSOL PHASE FUNCTION. THE ATMOSPHERIC SCATTERING PHASE FUNCTION AT SMALL SCATTERING ANGLES IS PRIMARILY CONTROLLED BY THE AEROSOL PARTICLE SIZE DISTRIBUTION AND IS LESS SENSITIVE TO OTHER PARAMETERS SUCH AS ATMOSPHERIC OPACITY OR PARTICLE SHAPE AND SINGLE-SCATTERING ALBEDO (CF. HANSEN AND TRAVIS, 1974, SPACE SCI. REV., 16, 527 610). MER NAVCAM DATA ARE IDEAL FOR THIS STUDY. THE MER NAVCAMS HAVE AN EFFECTIVE BAND-PASS WAVELENGTH OF ~650 NM (MAKI ET AL., 2003, JGR 108(E12)), SIMILAR TO THE EFFECTIVE PARTICLE SIZE OF MARS DUST AEROSOLS, RESULTING IN A STRONG DEPENDENCE IN THE WIDTH OF THE FORWARDSCATTERING PEAK TO AEROSOL PARTICLE SIZE. KEY TO THIS STUDY, THE NAVCAMS EXPERIENCE LITTLE-TO-NO DEBILITATING INTERNAL INSTRUMENTAL SCATTERED LIGHT DURING NEAR-SUN IMAGING, ENABLING MEASUREMENTS OF THE MARTIAN SKY DOWN TO SCATTERING ANGLES OF 1 TO 2 (SODERBLOM ET AL., 2008; JGR E06S19). PREVIOUS EFFORTS USING VIKING LANDER, MARS PATHFINDER, AND MER PANORAMIC CAMERA (PANCAM) IMAGES HAVE BEEN ABLE TO OBSERVE THE BRIGHTNESS OF THE MARTIAN SKY ONLY AT SCATTERING ANGLES>5 WHERE THE SENSITIVITY TO AEROSOL PARTICLE SIZE IS MUCH LESS. NAVCAM DATA THEREBY AFFORD A UNIQUE OPPORTUNITY TO MORE TIGHTLY CONSTRAIN THE PARTICLE SIZE DISTRIBUTION OF AEROSOLS IN THE MARTIAN ATMOSPHERE.

doc.ContractDescription: APPLICABILITY TO NASA EARTH SCIENCE (RELEVANCY SCENARIO) THE CONCEPT OF DISTRIBUTED MISSIONS WAS FIRST INVESTIGATED BETWEEN ABOUT 1998 AND 2002 THROUGH SEVERAL STUDIES FOCUSING MAINLY ON EARTH SCIENCE. SINCE THEN, THIS CONCEPT HAS NOT BEEN SYSTEMATICALLY INTEGRATED IN THE MAIN STREAM MISSIONS, E.G., DECADAL SURVEY MISSIONS, ALTHOUGH IT HAS BEEN CONSIDERED AND EVEN UTILIZED WHEN IT WAS THE ONLY SOLUTION CAPABLE TO SATISFY SOME GIVEN SCIENCE GOALS. NEVERTHELESS, THE CONCEPT CAN BE FOUND AGAIN IN MORE RECENT STUDIES; E.G., THE HELIOPHYSICS SYSTEM OBSERVATORY (HSO) MENTIONED IN THE 2010 NASA SCIENCE PLAN AND CONSTELLATIONS OF COMPLEMENTARY SATELLITES IN THE EARTH SCIENCE TECHNOLOGY OFFICE (ESTO) 2030 SCIENCE VISION. THIS GAP OF MORE THAN 10 YEARS IN THE INTEREST GIVEN TO DSM IS PROBABLY EXPLAINED BY THE COST AND POTENTIALLY THE COMPLEXITY ASSOCIATED WITH SUCH MISSIONS. THE HIGH COSTS THAT WERE ESTIMATED FOR POTENTIAL DSM WERE OFTEN THE CONSEQUENCE OF CONSTELLATION DESIGNS BASED ON REPEATING N TIMES THE DESIGN AND THE BUILDING OF ONE SPACECRAFT, THEREFORE LEADING TO COSTS BEING N TIMES THE COST OF A MONOLITHIC MISSION; THIS IS EXPLAINED NOT ONLY BY THE MISSION DESIGN ITSELF BUT ALSO BY COST MODELS THAT HAVE BEEN DESIGNED FOR MONOLITHIC MISSIONS AND DO NOT TAKE INTO ACCOUNT COST SAVINGS ASSOCIATED WITH ECONOMIES OF SCALE AND WITH RISK MINIMIZATION WHEN DEALING WITH DSM. ON THE OTHER HAND, IT IS TRUE THAT BUILDING A DISTRIBUTED MISSION ADDS TO THE COMPLEXITY OF THE MISSION, NOT ONLY IN THE DEVELOPMENT PHASE BUT ALSO IN THE OPERATIONAL PHASE, AND THIS COMPLEXITY TRANSLATES INTO ADDITIONAL COSTS AND RISK TO THE MISSION. THEREFORE, IT IS ONLY NOW THAT NEW TECHNOLOGIES AND CAPABILITIES SUCH AS SMALLSATS, CUBESATS, HOSTED PAYLOADS, ONBOARD COMPUTING, BETTER SPACE COMMUNICATIONS, AND GROUND SYSTEMS AUTOMATION HAVE APPEARED AND HAVE BECOME MATURE, THAT DSM SEEM TO BE FEASIBLE FOR A REASONABLE AND POTENTIALLY LOWER COST AND RISK THAN MONOLITHIC MISSIONS.
